At 8:49 am 19 years ago today, American Airlines Flight 11 struck the North World Trade Center Tower. Additionally, three more planes were hijacked which resulted in the terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001. Close to 3,000 people died on that horrific day. GHS students and staff took a moment of silence to honor all those who lost their lives on that tragic day. Thanks to the GHS choir who performed the Star Spangled Banner in their honor.

post_text:
Selected High school football teams across the state of Ohio will be wearing special jerseys at designated Military Appreciation games during the 2020 regular season, with help from the Ohio Army National Guard.

Goshen is excited to announce that we are one of the chosen schools and football teams to be honored with the wearing of these special camouflage jerseys at this week's game, Friday, September 11th, for our Military Appreciation Game.

Typically we honor our men and women who have served or who are serving our country with a cookout and halftime celebration at one of our home varsity football games. This year the special jersey night will be part of our Military/First Responder Appreciation Night. This opportunity is a great honor and a true tribute to the heroes of our community.

post_text:
We have developed two flow chart explaining the steps taken if a student or staff tests positive for COVID-19 or has been in close contact with someone who has tested positive for COVID-19. Please know any case or suspected case will be handled on an individual basis and communicated in collaboration with the Clermont County Public Health department.

Again we ask our families to play their role of symptom checking and keeping students home when they are sick. We have a plan that allows maximum safety at school, but it also relies on everyone playing their part at school and at home. We continue to be appreciative of our community, staff, and students' patience, flexibility, and understanding as we work to return our students to in-person and online learning models that meet the individual needs of their families. #weareinthistogether

post_text:
Today we want to talk about parents' and caregivers' roles in keeping the students at our school safe. Our motto has been ‚ÄúWe Are All in This Together‚Äù as we bring our students back for face to face instruction. Reopening of schools is not without risk and it is impossible to guarantee everyone‚Äôs safety. We have developed a great return plan. Here is how students and parents are a part of that safe return to school plan.
1. We need you to do a daily health symptom assessment prior to the arrival at school for each of your students.

2. If your child is sick we need you to keep them at home to protect all of the other students and staff.

3. Have your child complete all assignments they are given while out.

Under normal circumstances, Goshen Local Schools welcomes visitors to our campus. The COVID-19 pandemic is a difficult time for all of us. Safety is our number one priority, and we must do everything we can to prevent the spread of this disease and protect our students, faculty, and staff. post_text:
Good morning GHS Parents and Students,

In order to ensure the health and wellness of all GHS students, we will be modifying our morning arrival time. The building doors will be locked until 7:15 am.

Why the change? During a typical school year we have 100+ students that are in the building socializing until the school day starts. We obviously need to heighten safety measures in order to observe social distance regulations and our "norm" does not allow that.

This applies for both parent drop off and student drivers. Once you arrive at the building, you will enter the doors and report directly to 1st bell. Breakfast will be provided for students in 1st bell for those interested.

I ask for your flexibility and positivity as we move through the return to school.

Know that I appreciate all of you and we can't wait to see all our our GHS kids! We have been missing YOU!

post_text:
K-5 Staggered Start Implemented

Monday, August 24th- Only students with the last name A - K in grades K-5 attend school

Tuesday, August 25th- Only students with the last name L-Z in grades K-5 attend school

Wednesday, August 26th- All K-5 students attend

**** This does not impact the 6-12 student body or the students who signed up for the online platform.

Marr Cook and Spaulding administration will communicate building specific details in the next few days. A K-5 staggered start will ensure that all elementary students safely find their classrooms, get acquainted with their teachers, and are taught all-new safety procedures in the school buildings and on the buses in a more effective manner. Thank you for your patience and cooperation as we work to do what is best in such an unknown time.

post_text:
The Board of Education has approved a revised school calendar, which adds two additional teacher in-service days to the start of the school year.

As we continue to plan for the 2020-2021 school year, it has become apparent that we need additional time with our teachers and support staff in August to make sure we are ready to implement a safe and effective return to school plan under COVID restrictions.

August 20-21 which were originally the first days for students will now be teacher in-service days. The first day for students will now be on Monday, August 24. The remainder of the 2020-2021 school calendar remains unchanged at this point.

We will continue to work diligently for our students to develop the very best plan that provides a great education in a safe manner. The need for the two additional staff preparation days will help us do just that. As state guidance and plans are finalized, we will be sure to communicate them to you.

Second Grade Families:

Welcome to Spaulding Elementary!

We are excited that your soon-to-be third grader and family will be joining us at Spaulding Elementary next school year. We are sad that we have not been able to meet you and your child in person as we typically would in the spring with tours and our parent transition night.

Luckily, with technology, we are able to bring a tour to your device for you and your child to watch as well as the parent transition video which is full of information about Spaulding.

Please click on the link for the Third Grade Tour of Spaulding Elementary:

Please click on the link for the Third Grade Parent Transition presentation:

We look forward to a great three years with your child at Spaulding Elementary and cannot wait to meet your child and family!

post_text:
Congratulations is in order to 2019 graduate Ariya Bradley. Ariya has accepted an appointment to attend the United States Military Academy at West Point (USMA). Ari (as he his known to his classmates and teachers) also received an appointment to attend the United States Naval Academy at Annapolis, MD (USNA) and had to decline that appointment in order to join the United States Corps of Cadets (the official designation of the military unit to which cadets are assigned at West Point). He reports for Cadet Basic Training on ‚ÄúR-Day‚Äù (Reception Day for new Cadets) on June 29, 2020 to officially swear-in as a member of the class of 2024.

We are very proud of this Goshen graduate!!!

post_text:
*** We are running a second round of the student technology access survey to help us as we plan for the 2020-2021 school year. If you responded to the survey during round one you should NOT receive a call or email for round 2.

The Ohio Department of Education has asked all schools to collect information about the technology available in our students‚Äô homes.

While we do not yet know exactly what education will look like in the fall, we are committed to making sure that our students and families have the internet connection and computers needed to make the most of learning from home.

Goshen families that did not respond to survey round one will receive a phone call and an email containing a three question survey. You can do either phone or email, and need not do both.

Your feedback will help Goshen and the Ohio Department of Education as we prepare for the future. Thank you!

The Ohio Department of Education has asked all schools to collect information about the technology available in our students‚Äô homes.

While we do not yet know exactly what education will look like in the fall, we are committed to making sure that our students and families have the internet connection and computers needed to make the most of learning from home.

Beginning Friday at 3pm, families will receive a phone call and an email containing a three question survey. You can do either phone or email, and need not do both.

Your feedback will help Goshen and the Ohio Department of Education as we prepare for the future. Thank you!

post_text:
Hello, Warriors families!

As you know, GLSD mails a printed school year calendar to every home in the school district each July.

This calendar includes important school dates and fantastic photographs of our students and faculty.

What you may not know is that the process for creating the art for the calendar takes several weeks and hundreds or thousands of photos.

This year, for obvious reasons, we are missing our models: you!

So, we are asking you, our quarantined Warriors, to submit photos for us to use in the 2020-2021 school year calendar.

The theme for this year‚Äôs calendar is ‚ÄúIn This Together.‚Äù

We are seeking photos of students and families doing what Warriors do: smiling in the face of new challenges, supporting ourselves, our loved ones, and our community, facing new challenges with grit and a positive attitude, and WARRIORING UP!

So, post your photos here! We will choose photos to use in the calendar and other publications as we move into summer and a new school year.

Someone who has a communication impairment may have a difficult time saying speech sounds correctly, understanding what is said, using words correctly to form sentences, speaking smoothly, or being a part of social interactions.

Think of 5 sentences. Find ways to communicate these sentences without speaking or writing. Would it be easy or hard if people couldn‚Äôt understand you when you were speaking?

Attention Preschool parents: quarter 3 report cards are available in ProgressBook.

Most of you have not had reason to register for a ProgressBook account before now. Look in your email for a registration code and instructions for creating your ProgressBook Parent Access account.

If you have a preschool student and do not receive an email, it is because no email address is attached to your student in our system. If that is the case, use this form to submit a help request. We will reply and help you register.

https://www.goshenlocalschools.org/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=1689132&type=d&pREC_ID=form.GOSHEN-D.rTP1H0v.1nv

Please put *YOUR* email address in the "Goshen email address" field so we can reply and assist.

post_text: So Mr. Emerine's 3D printer is capable of larger projects. He has been working on a N95 mask today. These masks take approximately 5 hours to print. They are reusable and can be sanitized. The only piece that would need to be purchased is the filters that need to be replaced after each use. We will be working with our school resource officers to determine which organizations would benefit the most from these masks. Mr. Emerine also shared the file needed to print the masks with the Rolke family as they have also offered to produce these masks with their printers. Goshen is an amazing community! #WarriorUp

post_text: Mr. Emerine and Mrs. Slagle from GMS have been using our 3D printers to produce items for our first responders. Mrs. Slagle recorded a video describing the production of the mask holder. These take about 25 minutes to create and can be sterilized after use. We will be donating these once we have a set ready to go. Thank you for helping our first responders!

post_text:
Attention SENIORS and Families,
As you know, graduation is a milestone event that every student and family looks forward to. COVID-19 has caused many scheduling difficulties during the past few weeks. Students have reached out concerned that the May 27th graduation might be cancelled as well.

As of today, we plan to hold graduation as originally planned on May 27th. In the event that the governor extends the "stay at home order" we have secured a second graduation date. Mark your calendars for both dates at this time until we get further direction from the governor.

Original date: May 27th at 7 pm at BB&T Arena at NKU
Back-up date: July 17th at 7 pm at BB&T Arena at NKU

If you have questions, feel free to reach out to Mrs. Walker at walkers@goshenlocalschools.org

Have a great day! Mrs. Walker

https://drive.google.com/file/d/1l1Qs-UNu8jNBYQbUjv5nqAQkDyIeoBRq/view?usp=sharing
